description:
Tinea semifulvella is a small moth species belonging to the family Tineidae, commonly known as the "half-tawny Tinea". It is a member of the genus Tinea, which includes numerous species of clothes moths and carpet moths.

The Tinea semifulvella moth has a wingspan of approximately 12-16 millimeters. Its forewings are greyish-brown in color, with a distinctive golden-brown patch near the tip. The hindwings are greyish in color. The larvae of this species are typically pale in color and feed on a variety of organic materials, including fabrics, carpets, and other natural fibers.

Tinea semifulvella is widely distributed throughout Europe and Asia, and is considered a common and widespread species. It is often found in human-inhabited areas, where it can potentially cause damage to textiles and other household items. The species is of interest to entomologists and pest control professionals due to its role in the degradation of various natural materials.
